{ Welcome to the most comprehensive Anti Anti-Sicilian repertoire from Black's perspective in the world! Usually, I create lengthy intros  (which are probably skipped by 90% of users and I can't blame them!)  , but this time, I decided to do a shorter introduction!  Firstly, and most importantly, this course is designed for every Sicilian player who responds to 2.Nf3 with 2 ... d6 2... e6 or 2... Nc6.   I don't cover 2..Nf6, 2..a6 or 2..g6 etc. because I consider those to give White a little something, and 95%+ of Sicilians might be reached via ... d6 ... e6 or ... Nc6.  Secondly, this course is divided into four main parts which are:  1. Chapters #2 - #5 - for everybody! No matter if you play the Sveshnikov, Najdorf or Four Knights  (you rock!)  , you will meet the Morra, Alapin or 2.b3. That means that everybody can learn chapters #2 - #5.  2. Chapters #6 - #13 - for 2... e6 players only.  3. Chapters #14 - #25 - for 2... d6 players with the exceptions in chapters #14 and #19, which are also designed to suit 2... Nc6 players.  4. Chapters #26 - #30 - for 2... Nc6 players only.  Now, how to work with this course? It is obvious you don't need all of those chapters and you will learn only about half of them - that's what is usually necessary to be ready to meet all of the Anti-Sicilians that will harm your favourite move order.  A very simple trick is to click on the chapter you don't want and tick the Pause all chapters option -  - more on that in the video introduction for the course! You might simply customize the course so it suits you in the best way!  For example, if you play the Four Knights, then you only need chapters #2 - #13 and you might even skip no #5 because you have your own Alapin in #13.  If you play the Najdorf, you need #2 - #5 and #14 - #25 - so you pause everything else. You get the point!  Now the best thing! In a year from now, you will switch to the other Sicilian, for example now you play the Sveshnikov, and in a year you start the Dragon. You might simply pause 2... Nc6 chapters and stick to 2... d6 ones. Easy  The last thing I want to mention is how I use arrows. I created a system that goes like this:  1. green arrow - move/moves that we will most certainly play in the nearest future  2. blue arrow - general ideas in the positions/secondary plans  3. red arrows - bad pieces, weak squares, non-working plans  4. yellow arrows - either alternative options for us or how we react vs opponent's move.  I know that it might look confusing, so here you have some examples:  a. @@LinkStart@@https://www.chessable.com/variation/8226540/#/15/b@@LinkEnd@@ - a simple one - we will play ... Nb6 and the a4-pawn is weak - easy  b. @@LinkStart@@https://www.chessable.com/variation/8225940/#/8/b@@LinkEnd@@ - on move 8 White threatened Qxg7 and Qxd5, so now I highlight with red arrows those don't work. With the yellow arrows, you see that Nc7 runs into ... Nc6.  c. @@LinkStart@@https://www.chessable.com/variation/8225883/#/16/b@@LinkEnd@@ - here a creative example showing in three colours our responses to three different ideas; if Nh4 we play ... Nd5, if Bf4 we go ... Qxd4 and Be3 runs into ... Nc4.  d. @@LinkStart@@https://www.chessable.com/explore/edit/8225865/@@LinkEnd@@ - green arrows - our next two moves, blue arrows - moves we play after the green moves, yellow arrows show that if White goes f4 we strike with ... d6 or ... d5 and with the red circle I highlight the weakness of the e5-pawn.  e.@@LinkStart@@https://www.chessable.com/variation/8226400/#/11/b@@LinkEnd@@ - green arrow highlights we will play next, then blue arrow shows we will follow it up with ... e5 and the secondary plan is ... h6 followed by ... Qe8 - yellow arrows.  I am sure you get the point and the arrows are going to be a pleasant addition to the course!  Creating this course was the most challenging task for me so far, but I am proud of this work! As the main course page states, I made many boring lines not boring - which was my motto when working. Also, whenever I found out that a certain variation was analysed by the other author, I usually went for the alternative line to give you some fresh lines. I did my best to do the lines exciting and dynamic. I hope you will like this course. Get ready to beat your opponents who dare to skip 3. d4 on move three or play the Morra or Alapin!  Kamil Plichta }
