1. e4 c5
{ So here we are. I guess that if you purchased this course, you - like me - are a Sicilian player. I don't claim here that you are from Palermo or Catania, but that you like to play unbalanced chess by replying 1. e4 with 1... c5. In the first theoretical chapter  (which means the 2nd chapter of the course, since the 1st one is devoted to the intro)  , we will take a look at all of White's rare 2nd moves. Some of them are more playable and some are just dubious, but I wanted to cover all of the options that at least from time to time appear in tournament practice. Of course, don't expect me to cover 2. h3 or 2. a4 because you can get a decent position vs those moves without doing anything extraordinary. But any reasonable move from White that isn't a main-line has been covered. }
2. Be2
{ I consider this move to be the interesting one for White. Our opponent's idea is quite non-standard - White wants to play f4 next with a reversed Dutch setup ! White, therefore, avoids problems that can be seen in the 2. f4 d5 line. }
2... Nc6 3. f4
{ This is White's idea behind the move 2. Be2. White wants to play Nf3, d3, castle kingside and start some attack on the kingside. I recommend to immediately counter-attack in the centre. }
3... e6 { Black prepares a quick ... d5. } 4. Nf3 d5 5. e5
{ This is played from time to time but I think it is inferior to 5. d3. White shouldn't close the centre leaving us with the d5 - c5 pawn duo and the f5-square for the Knight. }
5... Nh6 { A typical plan of planting the Knight on f5. } 6. O-O Be7
{ It is also possible to put the Knight on f5 immediately but before we move the same piece twice, we will develop. }
7. c3
{ White is ready to play d4 and I would like to stop that plan immediately. }
7... d4
{ This move is a novelty but I really like this approach. We immediately stop White's d4, gain space in the centre and prepare to play ... b6 followed by ... Bb7 when the light-squared Bishop rules on the long diagonal. I don't claim that Black is better but in practical play, it should be much easier to play this position with Black. }
