1. e4 c5 2. c3
{ The so-called Alapin Variation championed by GM Evgeny Sveshnikov. White's idea is crystal-clear - push d4 and claim the centre. It is considered that Black has two main setups against White's system: 1 - 2... Nf6 which is a topic of this chapter; 2 - 2... d5 which I will analyse in the 2... e6 Alapin chapter - there we have to switch gears because the Alapin that I am going to discuss is reached via the 1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 e6 3. c3 move order. Note that in this chapter we avoid playing ... e6 which means that it was necessary to prepare an additional setup for Black.   Also note that if White starts with  2.Nf3  Nc6  3.c3  , it will sooner or later transpose to one of the main options from this chapter after  3...Nf6  4.e5  Nd5  White will now play either 5. Bc4 or 5. d4 reaching one of the main lines. }
2... Nf6
{ In my opinion, this is not only the most popular move and the best continuation at Black's disposal, but also the line that is the easiest to play and understand. Black will reach a highly improved version of the Alekhine, where the pawn on c3 is just badly placed. }
3. e5 Nd5 4. Nf3
{ This is the modern way of playing the Alapin. White postpones d4 and plans to put the Bishop on c4 to speed up his development. }
4... Nc6 5. g3
{ Playing for the fianchetto is possible but too slow. Black can get the upper hand by simple means. }
5... d6 6. exd6 Qxd6
{ Taking with the Queen is stronger because the Knight on d5 is protected and we might put some pressure on the d-file - especially the d3-square might be weak. }
7. Bg2 Bf5
{ Black already threatens to put the Bishop on d3 which leaves White with only one sensible option. }
8. d4 Qe6+ { Using the active Queen and forcing White to lose coordination. }
9. Qe2
{ 9.Kf1 ?!  Qd7  would lead to an improved version of the 2. g3 lines from the first theoretical chapter of this course. }
9... Qxe2+ 10. Kxe2 e6
{ Black has a normal position with the White King on e2. Despite the fact it is the endgame, the King might feel a little heat in the centre of the board. Black's basic plan is to castle long - but watch out for Ng5 jumps - with or without ... f6 included. Sometimes ... Rd8 followed by ... Be7 / ... Bd6 and short castle will be a decent plan. }
