3... d5
{ And that means that we have to have a back-up line against the Alapin. Of course, playing 3... Nf6 is possible, but not to my liking and I recommend to learn this line ! I will tell you in secret that there is another option ! You might skip learning 2... Nf6 whatsoever, and abandon the 5th chapter, just to use this line as your primary weapon against the Alapin. The choice is yours, but I personally plan to learn both lines and use them both. Not only you become much less predictable, but also, you learn new pawn structures and how to play them. And this is one of the best ways of widening your general knowledge and chess culture. }
4. e5
{ White might avoid typical Alapin lines connected with the move exd5. The text move secures White some space advantage and - if we are not careful - transpose to the Advanced French after d4 ! I don't claim that the Advanced French is a great opening, but allowing that forces us to go outside of the scope of this repertoire. }
4... d4
{ Not only declining White the option of going for the Advanced French but also grabbing some space and creating immediate tension. }
5. cxd4
{ Taking on d4 frees the c3-square for the Knight but it commits to having a backward d-pawn and frees our dark-squared Bishop. }
5... cxd4 6. Qa4+
{ It surprises me how popular this move is. Amazingly, White is much worse now! }
6... Nc6 7. Bb5 Bd7 8. Bxc6 Bxc6 9. Qxd4 Ne7
{ Black will take on f3 forcing the exchange of Queens. Then ... Nc6 is with tempo on the e5-pawn allowing us to play ... Nb4 next with positional domination. }
