{ I consider this particular move order to be quite annoying. The reason for that is simple - in the 5th chapter of this course, I recommended to play the 2... Nf6 line against the Alapin. If you worked with that chapter, you will for sure remember me mentioning on multiple occasions that we want to AVOID playing ... e6 too early. The reason for that was that moves such as ... d6 and ... Nc6 are much more efficient in attacking White's centre in the Alapin. And when you look at the position that is in front of you - the pawn is already on e6  (BASTARD !)  . }
3... d5
{ And that means that we have to have a back-up line against the Alapin. Of course, playing 3... Nf6 is possible, but not to my liking and I recommend to learn this line ! I will tell you in secret that there is another option ! You might skip learning 2... Nf6 whatsoever, and abandon the 5th chapter, just to use this line as your primary weapon against the Alapin. The choice is yours, but I personally plan to learn both lines and use them both. Not only you become much less predictable, but also, you learn new pawn structures and how to play them. And this is one of the best of widening your general knowledge and chess culture. }
4. exd5 { The main variation and the most typical for the Alapin. } 4... Qxd5
{ I consider this to be a better reaction if you want to play for the win. Taking with the pawn is a more solid option but it leads to symmetrical pawn structures when playing dry, technical chess is the key. As usual, I prefer to avoid very calm positions and look for more dynamic options. }
5. d4
{ Virtually the only move. In the other systems of the Alapin, it is possible to postpone d4 and play with some flank options such as Na3, but in this line, it is not dangerous. }
5... Nf6 6. Be2
{ One of the most popular moves. White avoids any skirmish and plans to develop normally. Also, having the Bishop on e2 prepares dxc5 since the Queen on d1 is protected. }
6... cxd4
{ With dxc5 being an option for White, I believe that taking on d4 is the most topical line. Allowing White to take on c5 was also an option, but I just prefer to avoid that. }
7. cxd4 Qd6
{ This is my recommended move order to stop the Bf4 line. After Nc3 and Nc6 we will transpose to the mainline, but eliminating the Bf4 line by using a smart move order is a nice thing for us. }
8. Nc3 Nc6
{ Back in the mainline. We could also consider putting the Queen on d8 but in this particular line I think that we can get a good position by keeping the Lady more active. }
9. O-O Be7 10. Nb5
{ White tries to exploit our Queen on d6 but with the King being one step from castling, this should be harmless. }
10... Qd8
{ The best square. On d7 the Queen would ask for Ne5 jumps and going to b8 is just anti-positional. This is the Anti-Sicilian course, not anti-positional one ! }
11. Bf4 { The most active move threatening problems on c7. } 11... Nd5
{ We should defend against White's invasion on c7 before castling. } 12. Bg3
O-O 13. Bc4 { The main move. } 13... a6
{ White didn't do anything to stop our ... a6 and ... b5 break so we continue with the standard plan. }
14. Bxd5
{ White creates an isolated d-pawn in our camp too but he gets rid of the light-squared Bishop. }
14... exd5 { 14...axb5  15.Be4  doesn't convince me. } 15. Nc7 Rb8 16. Ne5
{ A key move creating more tension in the position. } 16... Bf6
{ Black creates a threat of his own - ... Bxe5 followed by ... Qxc7. } 17. Rc1
Bxe5 { The Knight has to be eliminated. } 18. Bxe5
{ 18.dxe5  Be6  is the simplest with the point that after  19.Nxa6  bxa6  20.Rxc6  there is  20...Rxb2  with more or less equal chances. }
18... Bf5 19. Qf3 { The best try for White. } 19... Nxe5 20. dxe5 Be4 21. Qf4
Rc8 22. e6 fxe6 23. Qe5 Qd7 24. Qxe6+ Qf7
{ Black managed to completely equalize and will retake on f7 with the King. I think that we have good chances to play for the win having the Bishop in an open position. }
