1. e4 c5 2. Nc3 d6
{ Starting from this chapter, we will start looking at all of Black's variations after the move 2... d6. Logically - as in the 2... e6 chapters - we will start by analyzing 2nd move options, then 3rd, 4th etc. There will be a total number of 12 chapters devoted to all kinds of 2... d6 lines. We start by analyzing the Closed Variation. }
3. g3
{ The so-called Closed Variation of the Sicilian which was championed by Boris Spassky. White abandons plans connected with d4 and will play a slower game. Usually, White will build up on the kingside and Black will look for his chances on the queenside. This chapter is quite big not because White's setup is dangerous, but due to the fact that that White has many different move orders and setups possible. }
3... Nc6
{ Note that players who play 2... Nc6 with Black should also learn this chapter as after 2... Nc6 3. g3 d6 we just transpose to this chapter ! }
4. Bg2 g6
{ The best plan is to fianchetto the Bishop. There are a few reasons for that: 1  White doesn't have the option of playing c3 to block the Bishop; 2  The d4-square is under our control and the Bishop will be very active; 3  There is not a better option to develop the Bishop since we have three pawns blocking the a3 - f8 diagonal. }
5. d3
{ Sooner or later this move is going to be played so I cover only this move order. }
5... Bg7 6. f4
{ One of the most aggressive option. White will continue with Nf3, Nge2 or sometimes Nh3. Note that the lines connected with the move Nh3 are going to be analysed via the 6. Nh3 move order. }
6... Rb8
{ This plan is copied from the English Opening. Before committing to anything on the kingside, it is useful to prepare quick counterplay with ... b5. Then we can adjust our plan depending on White's setup. }
7. Nge2
{ I think that this plan is inconsistent with the previous continuation. White's dream setup is to get f5 in and Nf4 next. }
7... e6
{ Knowing that the Knight on e2 makes sense only with a combination of f5, it is useful to stop White's plan by slowing it down. ... Nge7 is next. }
8. O-O Nge7 { F5 is more or less stopped. } 9. g4
{ Remember the theme, that whenever there is a pawn trio on g4 f4 and e4, we reply with ... f5 immediately! White's ideas connected with ... f5 should be stopped. }
9... f5
{ More than 10 years ago I read the rule that if White captures on f5 we should recapture asymmetrically. That means that if the g-pawn takes we should take back with the e-pawn and if the e-pawn takes then we take back with the g-pawn. However, now I have another rule - virtually always take back with the e-pawn! When working on this course, I checked some situations with captures for White, and in ALL of them ... exf5 was the best choice - no matter what White takes with! }
10. Ng3 O-O
{ Black is already slightly better. Our setup is more compact and we have many dynamic options. }
11. h3 b6
{ I like this plan more than going for ... b5. We prepare to develop the Bishop to b7 and eventually play ... d5. Note that ... Qd7 might be an interesting strengthening move. }
