{ This is the line that is played in about 2% of games but I think it deserves to be covered. White postpones the queenside Knight's development to be able to play c4 and set up the Maroczy structure. Note that the Maroczy structure is something that you see most often in the openings such as Kan/ Paulsen or Accelerated Dragon, but vs 2... d6, there is no way for White to set up this structure in a standard way. By starting with f3, White wants to play c4 next, and unless you are a huge fan of the Maroczy with Black, you should stop this pawn thrust whatsoever! }
5... e5
{ The most critical way of playing is to seize space in the centre. It weakens the d5-square but don't worry - we will deal with that on the next move. }
6. Bb5+
{ This is supposed to be a disruptive check in many Sicilian positions, but it is not too strong with the pawn on f3. }
6... Nbd7
{ We avoid the Bishops exchange which helps us cover the light squares in the centre. }
7. Nf5
{ White has a strong Knight on f5 but with the combination of the Bishop on b5, those pieces are not too stable. }
7... d5
{ This move involves a pawn sacrifice but there are some conditions that support this sacrifice. Firstly, White made three moves with the Knight. Secondly, f3 was played which weakens the pawn cover around the White King. }
8. exd5 { There is nothing else. } 8... a6
{ We gain several tempos on the White pieces now and our development will be smooth like the interview between Magnus Carlsen and Maurice Ashley. }
