{ This is the move order designed to trick Sveshnikov players from their favourite system. The point is that now 3... Nf6 ?! would be answered with 4. Bb5, with a position that I would prefer to avoid. }
3... e5
{ This is the recommended move order for the Sveshnikov players. However, if you play the Classical, Taimanov or Accelerated Dragon, there is some good news for you!   Accelerated Dragon people can continue with  3...g6  , and they should be happy to avoid Maroczy lines! If White decides not to transpose into the Open Sicilian and play  4.Bb5  instead, we directly transpose to the next chapter devoted to the Rossolimo.   If you play the Classical Sicilian, then  3...d6  is perfectly acceptable. After  4.Bb5  we are back in the #22nd chapter.   The last possible move is  3...e6  , which should be considered by Taimanov players. If White avoids transposing into the Open Sicilian and go for  4.Bb5  - check out the #8th chapter.  However, if you are a Sveshnikov/Kalashnikov player, I recommend continuing with the text move. Black stops d4 and discourages Bb5, because we will be able to answer that with ... d6 keeping a strong centre. }
4. Bc4
{ White's setup makes perfect sense because our ... d5 square will be weak forever. There is no way we will be able to play ... d5, so we have to deal with the fact that it won't be possible. We will calmly develop the kingside and then decide what to do next. }
4... Be7 5. d3 { 5.O-O  d6  6.d3  is the same. } 5... d6 6. Nd2
{ This is a smart line that postpones castling for one simple reason. White wants to put the Knight on e3 via f1. After castling it would take more time, since the f1-square would be occupied by the Rook. }
6... Bg5
{ This is the additional option that we get. Note that the dark-squared Bishop is considered a bad piece because it is blocked by the pawns on e5, d6 and c5. From a strategic point of view, it is useful to exchange it for one of White's pieces. It is a typical positional theme for the Sveshnikov. Also, note that these positions might be all about the d5-square. A dream scenario for White would be to post the Knight on d5 and leave us with the dark-squared Bishop. Here, it won't be possible because we will exchange that piece. }
7. Nf1 { Allowing Black to carry through the exchange should ease our task. }
7... Bxc1 8. Qxc1 Be6
{ It is necessary to challenge White's light-squared Bishop. We don't put it here to take on c4, since it would weaken the light squares in the centre even more. We put the Bishop on e6 to provoke White into taking, and then the new pawn on e6 will help cover d5. }
9. Ne3 Nge7 10. O-O Ng6 { A novelty stopping f4. } 11. Qd2
{ White just develops the Queen and connects the Rooks. } 11... O-O 12. Ncd5
{ Note that we rarely want to take on d5 with the Bishop. We need our guy on e6 to protect some of the light squares. A typical plan will be to continue with ... Nce7 to challenge the Knight on d5. }
12... Nce7 13. Nxe7+ Nxe7 14. b4
{ 14.f4  exf4  15.Rxf4  Qd7  followed by ... b5 or even in some positions ... d5. }
14... Rc8
{ Preparing to recapture on c5 with the Rook. Black is ready to play ... d5. }
15. Bxe6 fxe6 16. b5 Ng6 17. g3 Rc7
{ The Rook will be transferred to f7, and then we will play ... Qg5 or ... h5 - h4 with pressure on the kingside. }
